snippet.textDisplay: I've loved all the other live-action Disney Princess remakes so far, but I'm just not sure about this one.  I mean, they've already made the movie not as kid friendly as the animated version just by making a warrior movie where a young woman kills thousands of enemies live action and then they had to take out Mushu, the cricket, and all the songs, which were a huge part of what made the animated version so great in my opinion, and then they had to add an evil witch, which also doesn't seem that kid friendly to me, especially if it's in a live-action movie.  I really wanted to give this remake a chance, but I'm just not sure it'll be good.  It DOES come out right around my birthday, but I don't know if I'll go see it or not.

snippet.textDisplay: People love saying "wow you have room for a shapeshifting witch but not Mushu?" but they need to understand the difference in culture. Shapeshifting witches were common in Chinese Mythology. Either they were animals that can turn human, or humans that can turn into animals, either way they were prominent in Mythology. Mushu on the other hand, was a mini-dragon, who was goofy and clumsy, which strayed veryyyyy far away from mythology. Maybe he would have fit if he was a huge, benevolent, God-like creature in the film that had no comedy factor, but he wouldn't hide very well. So yeah, there's a difference that people have to understand.

snippet.textDisplay:
The "Ballad of Mulan"（《木蘭辭》） is a folksong from Northern and Southern Dynasties Period (南北朝，330-581)China. It recounts the story of Mulan, a girl who goes to war in place of her father. The pseudo-historical personage of Mulan probably lived in the fifth century, when the Toba【鮮卑拓跋氏, Royal family of Northern Wei Dynasty(北魏，386-534), clan of the Xianbei people in ancient China】, who dominated north China, were engaged in a long war with the Rouran(柔然) on their northern frontier. It is thought the ballad was collected into an anthology of yuefu (樂府詩)in the mid-sixth century, and later popularised during the Tang Dynasty(唐，618-907).

作者不明，為中國自南北朝時代開始流傳的一首敘事詩，訴說女英雄木蘭代父從軍的傳奇故事。

《古詩賞析·十一》引《名勝志》載：「木蘭村在湖廣黃州府治北六十里，其上有木蘭將軍場。『木蘭』者，朱氏女，詐為男子，代父西征。」

Ballad of Mulan
《木蘭辭》
Translated by Jack Yuan

The sound of one sigh after another,
唧唧復唧唧
As Mulan weaves at the doorway.
木蘭當戶織
No sound of the loom and shuttle,
不聞機杼聲
Only that of the girl lamenting.
惟聞女歎息
Ask her of whom she thinks,
問女何所思
Ask her for whom she longs.
問女何所憶
"There is no one I think of,
女亦無所思
There is no one I long for.
女亦無所憶
Last night I saw the army notice,
昨夜見軍帖
The Khan is calling a great draft –
可汗大點兵
A dozen volumes of battle rolls,
軍書十二卷
Each one with my father's name.
卷卷有爺名
My father has no grown-up son,
阿爺無大兒
And I have no elder brother.
木蘭無長兄
I'm willing to buy a horse and saddle,
願為市鞍馬
To go to battle in my father's place."
從此替爺征

She buys a fine steed at the east market;
東市買駿馬
A saddle and blanket at the west market;
西市買鞍韉
A bridle at the south market;
南市買轡頭
And a long whip at the north market.
北市買長鞭
She takes leave of her parents at dawn,
旦辭爺娘去
To camp beside the Yellow River at dusk.
暮宿黃河邊
No sound of her parents hailing their girl,
不聞爺娘喚女聲
Just the rumbling waters of the Yellow River.
但聞黃河流水鳴濺濺
She leaves the Yellow River at dawn,
旦辭黃河去
To reach the Black Mountains by dusk.
暮至黑山頭
No sound of her parents hailing their girl,
不聞爺娘喚女聲
Just the cries of barbarian cavalry in the Swift Mountains.
但聞燕山胡騎鳴啾啾


Ten thousand miles she rode in war,
萬裡赴戎機
Crossing passes and mountains as if on a wing.
關山度若飛
On the northern air comes the sentry's gong,
朔氣傳金柝
Cold light shines on her coat of steel.
寒光照鐵衣
The general dead after a hundred battles,
將軍百戰死
The warriors return after ten years.
壯士十年歸


They return to see the Son of Heaven,
歸來見天子
Who sits in the Hall of Brilliance.
天子坐明堂
The rolls of merit spin a dozen times,
策勛十二轉
Rewards in the hundreds and thousands.
賞賜百千強
The Khan asks her what she desires,
願賜木蘭賞
"I've no need for the post of a gentleman official,
不用尚書郎
I ask for the swiftest horse,
明駝千裡足
To carry me back to my hometown."
送兒還故鄉


Her parents hearing their girl returns,
爺娘聞女來
Out to the suburbs to welcome her back.
出郭相扶將
Elder sister hearing her sister returns,
阿姊聞妹來
Adjusts her rouge by the doorway.
當戶理紅妝
Little brother hearing his sister returns,
小弟聞姊來
Sharpens his knife for pigs and lamb.
磨刀霍霍向豬羊
"I open my east chamber door,
開我東閣門
And sit on my west chamber bed.
坐我西閣床
I take off my battle cloak,
脫我戰時袍
And put on my old-time clothes.
著我舊時裳
I adjust my wispy hair at the window sill,
當窗理雲鬢
And apply my bisque makeup by the mirror.
對鏡貼花黃
I step out to see my comrades-in-arms,
出門看火伴
They are all surprised and astounded:
火伴皆驚忙
'We travelled twelve years together,
同行十二載
Yet didn't realise Mulan was a lady!'"
不知木蘭是女郎

The buck bounds here and there,
雄兔腳撲朔
Whilst the doe has narrow eyes.
雌兔眼迷離
But when the two rabbits run side by side,
雙兔傍地走
How can you tell the female from the male?
安能辨我是雄雌！
snippet.textOriginal:
The "Ballad of Mulan"（《木蘭辭》） is a folksong from Northern and Southern Dynasties Period (南北朝，330-581)China. It recounts the story of Mulan, a girl who goes to war in place of her father. The pseudo-historical personage of Mulan probably lived in the fifth century, when the Toba【鮮卑拓跋氏, Royal family of Northern Wei Dynasty(北魏，386-534), clan of the Xianbei people in ancient China】, who dominated north China, were engaged in a long war with the Rouran(柔然) on their northern frontier. It is thought the ballad was collected into an anthology of yuefu (樂府詩)in the mid-sixth century, and later popularised during the Tang Dynasty(唐，618-907).
